I0319 17:37:33.882594 125263652324928 reward_manager.py:164] prompts:	Tom is on a road trip and wants to know how far he can travel in a certain amount of time. He knows that his car's fuel efficiency is 30 miles per gallon, and he has 15 gallons of gas in the tank. If he drives at an average speed of 45 miles per hour, how many hours can he drive before running out of gas?
I0319 17:37:33.882704 125263652324928 reward_manager.py:164] completions:	 To determine how long Tom can drive before running out of gas, we need to calculate the total distance he can travel with his current fuel supply and then divide that distance by his average speed.

First, we calculate the total distance Tom can travel with 15 gallons of gas. Given that his car's fuel efficiency is 30 miles per gallon, we use the following formula:
\[
\text{Total Distance} = \text{Fuel Efficiency} \times \text{Fuel in Tank}
\]
Substituting the given values:
\[
\text{Total Distance} = 30 \, \text{miles per gallon} \times 15 \, \text{gallons} = 450 \, \text{miles}
\]

Next, we need to determine how long it will take Tom to travel 450 miles at an average speed of 45 miles per hour. We use the formula:
\[
\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Total Distance}}{\text{Average Speed}}
\]
Substituting the values:
\[
\text{Time} = \frac{450 \, \text{miles}}{45 \, \text{miles per hour}} = 10 \, \text{hours}
\]

Thus, Tom can drive for \boxed{10} hours before running out of gas.
