Since the hexagon is regular and symmetric, the triangles formed by the diagonals and midpoints will have proportional areas. The key is to recognize that the areas of triangles formed by the diagonals and midpoints of the hexagon are related by the properties of similar triangles and the symmetry of the hexagon.

Since the hexagon is divided into 6 equilateral triangles by its diagonals, and considering the symmetry, the area of triangle \( ACM \) is equal to the area of triangle \( FNH \). Therefore, the ratio of the area of triangle \( ACM \) to the area of triangle \( FNH \) is \( 1 \).

