First, compute the product of the matrices:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} a & -1 \\ 2 & a \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a \cdot 2 + (-1) \cdot (-3) \\ 2 \cdot 2 + a \cdot (-3) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2a + 3 \\ 4 - 3a \end{pmatrix}.
\]
Next, subtract the vector \(\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}\) from the result:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} 2a + 3 \\ 4 - 3a \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2a + 3 - 4 \\ 4 - 3a - 7 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2a - 1 \\ -3a - 3 \end{pmatrix}.
\]
The norm of this vector is given by:
\[
\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2a - 1 \\ -3a - 3 \end{pmatrix} \right\| = \sqrt{(2a-1)^2 + (-3a-3)^2}.
\]
We are given that this norm equals \(2\sqrt{13}\), so we set up the equation:
\[
\sqrt{(2a-1)^2 + (-3a-3)^2} = 2\sqrt{13}.
\]
Square both sides of the equation to eliminate the square root:
\[
(2a-1)^2 + (-3a-3)^2 = (2\sqrt{13})^2.
\]
Simplify the right side and expand the left side:
\[
(2a-1)^2 + (-3a-3)^2 = 4 \cdot 13 = 52.
