\]
To eliminate the fractions, we can multiply every term by 10:
\[
10y - 55 = -6x + 21
\]
Rearranging terms, we get:
\[
6x + 10y = 76
\]
Dividing by 2, we have:
\[
3x + 5y = 38
\]
This is the equation of the line on which the point where Peggy and Timmy will meet lies. However, since they are standing equidistant from the origin, the point they meet must be on the perpendicular bisector and equidistant from the origin. The point \(\left( \frac{7}{2}, \frac{11}{2} \right)\) is the only point that satisfies both conditions, so the coordinates of the point where they will meet are:
\[
