4. Using the property that \(a \log_b(c) = \log_b(c^a)\), we can rewrite the right-hand side as \(\log_3(y) = \log_3(5^{z/2})\).
5. Since the logarithms on both sides of the equation have the same base, we can equate the arguments, giving us \(y = 5^{z/2}\).

