The key insight is that the sum of absolute deviations from a set of points is minimized when \( x \) is the median of the points. For an even number of points, the median is the average of the two middle points. Here, the points are \( 1, 2, 3, \ldots, 50 \), so the median is the average of the 25th and 26th points, which is \( \frac{25 + 26}{2} = 25.5 \).

We will evaluate \( S(x) \) at \( x = 25.5 \) and ensure that the value is the minimum.

First, consider \( x = 25.5 \):
\[ S(25.5) = |25.5 - 1| + |25.5 - 2| + \ldots + |25.5 - 25| + |25.5 - 26| + \ldots + |25.5 - 50|. \]

This can be broken into two parts:
\[ S(25.5) = (1 + 2 + \ldots + 25) + (26 + 27 + \ldots + 50). \]

The sum of the first 25 positive integers is:
\[ 1 + 2 + \ldots + 25 = \frac{25 \cdot 26}{2} = 325. \]

The sum of the integers from 26 to 50 is:
\[ 26 + 27 + \ldots + 50 = (1 + 2 + \ldots + 50) - (1 + 2 + \ldots + 25) = \frac{50 \cdot 51}{2} - 325 = 1275 - 325 = 950. \]

Therefore,
\[ S(25.5) = 325 + 950 = 1275. \]

To confirm that this is the minimum, we note that for any \( x \) other than 25.5, the sum \( S(x) \) will be greater than 1275. If \( x \) is less than 25.5, then \( |x - k| \) for \( k \) from 1 to 25 will be larger than if \( x \) were 25.5, and similarly if \( x \) is greater than 25.5, then \( |x - k| \) for \( k \) from 26 to 50 will be larger than if \( x \) were 25.5.

Thus, the minimum value of \( S(x) \) is \( \boxed{1275} \).
