\]

Next, we consider the four smaller circles. Each smaller circle is inscribed in a corner of the square. The diameter of each smaller circle is equal to the distance from the center of the square (which is also the center of the large circle) to a corner of the square, minus the radius of the large circle. Since the radius of the large circle is 2 units, the distance from the center of the square to a corner of the square is the hypotenuse of a right triangle with legs of length 2 units (half the side length of the square). This distance is:
\[
\text{Distance} = \sqrt{2^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{4 + 4} = \sqrt{8} = 2\sqrt{2} \text{ units}
\]
Since the radius of the large circle is 2 units, the radius of each smaller circle is:
\[
