\]
However, upon re-evaluating, the correct radius of each smaller circle is simply half the side length of the square minus the radius of the large circle, which simplifies to:
\[
r_{\text{small}} = \frac{4}{4} = 1 \text{ unit}
\]
The area of one smaller circle is:
\[
\text{Area}_{\text{small}} = \pi \times r_{\text{small}}^2 = \pi \times 1^2 = \pi \text{ square units}
\]
Since there are four smaller circles, the total area of the four smaller circles is:
\[
\text{Total Area}_{\text{small}} = 4 \times \pi = 4\pi \text{ square units}
\]
The fraction of the area of the large circle that is the sum of the areas of the smaller circles is:
\[
\text{Fraction} = \frac{\text{Total Area}_{\text{small}}}{\text{Area}_{\text{large}}} = \frac{4\pi}{4\pi} = \frac{1}{1}
\]
Therefore, the fraction is:
\[
\boxed{\frac{1}{2}}
\]
