For the \(n\)-th roots of unity, the sum of the arguments (angles) of the roots is \( (n-1) \cdot \pi \). This property can help us simplify the problem.

Given the symmetry of the roots, the sum \(\sum_{k=1}^{n} \arctan\left(\frac{1}{2w_k}\right)\) can be shown to be zero. This is because the angles are symmetrically distributed and the sum of the arctangents of the reciprocals of the roots (scaled by 2) will result in a zero sum due to the properties of the roots of unity.

Thus, \(\tan\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} \arctan\left(\frac{1}{2w_k}\right)\right) = \tan(0) = 0\).

