First, note that for any integer \( m \),
\[ \lfloor \sqrt{n} \rfloor = m \]
if and only if
\[ m^2 \leq n < (m+1)^2. \]
This means that the number \( m \) will appear in the sequence for all \( n \) in the interval \( [m^2, (m+1)^2 - 1] \). The length of this interval is
\[ (m+1)^2 - 1 - m^2 + 1 = 2m + 1. \]
Therefore, the number \( m \) will appear \( 2m + 1 \) times in the sequence.

The position at which the number \( k \) first appears is the cumulative sum of the number of times each previous number appears up to \( k-1 \), plus 1. This is because the first appearance of \( k \) is after all the numbers less than \( k \) have appeared.

The total number of terms up to and including the last appearance of \( k-1 \) is
\[ \sum_{m=1}^{k-1} (2m + 1) = (2 + 4 + 6 + \cdots + 2(k-1) + 1) = k^2. \]
Thus, the position where \( k \) first appears is \( k^2 \).

To see why, consider the sequence:
- The number 1 appears once (from 1 to 1).
- The number 2 appears 5 times (from 2 to 8).
- The number 3 appears 7 times (from 9 to 25).
- And so on...

So, the position where \( k \) first appears is indeed \( k^2 \).

Therefore, the position in the sequence where the number \( k \) appears for the first time is \(\boxed{k^2}\).
