I0319 22:12:58.329198 125263652324928 reward_manager.py:164] completions:	 To determine how long Mark has to wait for Alex to catch up, we first need to calculate the time it takes for each of them to complete the 50-mile coastal path.

First, we calculate the time it takes for Mark to cycle 50 miles. Mark's speed is 25 miles per hour, so the time \( t_M \) it takes for Mark to complete the path is:
\[
t_M = \frac{50 \text{ miles}}{25 \text{ miles per hour}} = 2 \text{ hours}
\]

Next, we calculate the time it takes for Alex to cycle 50 miles. Alex's speed is 15 miles per hour, so the time \( t_A \) it takes for Alex to complete the path is:
\[
t_A = \frac{50 \text{ miles}}{15 \text{ miles per hour}} = \frac{50}{15} = \frac{10}{3} \approx 3.33 \text{ hours}
\]

The difference in time between Alex and Mark is the amount of time Mark has to wait for Alex to catch up. This difference \( t \) is:
\[
t = t_A - t_M = \frac{10}{3} - 2 = \frac{10}{3} - \frac{6}{3} = \frac{4}{3} \approx 1.33 \text{ hours}
\]

Therefore, Mark has to wait \(\boxed{\frac{4}{3}}\) hours for Alex to catch up.
